ass=title>   Call to Battle</span><hr size=1> Cerres sat at the dining room table, open history books sprawled across it, taking notes which mostly consisted of doodles.  She tried to apply herself, but it was just so boring.  She liked the strategy parts, where the generals laid out methodology for taking certain regions.  But the who ruled what land parcel when and why so-and-so's brother's cousin had a feud just bored her to tears.  Cyris explained to her the world was filled with politics and understanding history would help her understand more clearly the events of today.  But it was all over Cerres' head and nothing she could do could make her interested.<br>
<br>
She quickly hid her doodles and started copying randomly from an open book as she heard the door open.  Hard footsteps echoed on the floor and Cerres looked up and screamed.  &quot;DADDY!!!!&quot;  She ran and jumped into Sylvanar's arms as he swung her around and placed her delicately back on her feet.<br>
<br>
&quot;My princess.  I have missed you.&quot;  Seeing the books sprawled on the table he looked at her quizically.  &quot;Don't tell me you're actually studying.&quot;<br>
<br>
Cerres pouted.  &quot;Cyris and Master Songweaver are in kahoots, Daddy.  They won't even let me re-apply until I've caught up on all my studies.&quot;<br>
<br>
Sylvanar laughed.  &quot;Oh, that is unfair.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Well, it is!  Why can't they see I'm a musician and not a scholar?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Every child in Kelethin over the age of 10 has studied those books,&quot; Cyris commented as he entered the room. &quot;They are hardly worth the attention of a scholar.&quot;  Cyris hugged Lord Sylvanar.  &quot;Father, it's good to have you home.  Will you be here long?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I'm afraid not.&quot;<br>
<br>
Cerres frowned.  &quot;Oh Daddy, you're never home.  Please stay.&quot;<br>
<br>
Sylvanar sat down at the table and pulled Cerres into his lap.  &quot;I'm afraid I can't, Princess.  The Tier'Dah have captured a ranger and are keeping him jailed.   The rangers are mounting a rescue effort as we speak.  I just came for my mask of deception and a meal before I join them.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;But can't it wait just a day?&quot;  Cerres said, a slight curl to her bottom lip.<br>
<br>
&quot;Every day we wait, princess, is a day of untold pain.  The Tier'Dal are not kind to their prisoners.  He will be beaten and tortured to within an inch of his life and brought back to life only enough to experience the agony of their methods.  The Tier'Dal pride themselves on the amount of pain they can inflict while keeping the being conscious.  Now, what would you want other fathers to do if I was the one in their hands?  Would you want them to wait a day?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;You'd never get caught, Daddy.  You're too smart.&quot;  Cerres chirped with pride.<br>
<br>
Sylvanar sighed.  &quot;Oh princess, you are such an innocent.&quot;  Sylvanar kissed Cerres on the forehead and held her tightly too him.  <br>
<br>
Cyris noticed that the weight of many battles seemed to be taking its toll on Sylvanar.  The mirth in his eyes had turned to sorrow.  His proud stance seemed slightly broken.  For the first time in his life, Cyris realized his father was getting old.  &quot;Do you have sufficient healers, Father?  I can come and help.&quot;<br>
<br>
Sylvanar smiled at his son.  &quot;No, son.  Their forces are too cunning.  Only those with significant battle experience will be going, and our forces will be small.  An invading army will never take Neriak.  But a few carefully placed assassins just may be able to free our brother.&quot;  <br>
<br>
<br>
